00:04:04.479 --> 00:04:10.399
So, today we're going to be talking about Cordo, and if you have not heard of Cordo before,

00:04:10.399 --> 00:04:14.800
it's an open source scientific and technical publishing system based on,

00:04:15.759 --> 00:04:22.559
built on Pandoc. So, let's break this down. So, open source means that Posit believes it's

00:04:22.559 --> 00:04:27.839
better if tools for research are free and open, which means more reproducibility and sharing of

00:04:27.839 --> 00:04:34.000
knowledge and techniques and elimination of cost barriers. Scientific and technical means that

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:41.119
Cordo has very specific things for journal articles or scientific papers, like support

00:04:41.119 --> 00:04:47.279
for code execution, equations, footnotes, scientific workdowns, citations, and so on.

00:04:49.119 --> 00:04:56.480
It's a publishing system, so that means you take output from R, Python, or Julia, or Observable,

00:04:56.480 --> 00:05:02.559
you take text written in a markdown, and then you render it to create high-quality articles,

00:05:02.559 --> 00:05:08.799
reports, presentations, websites, blogs, books, and so on in a bunch of formats as well,

00:05:08.799 --> 00:05:19.040
HTML, PDF, MS Word, EPUB, and more. And the last bit, Pandoc, is the tool working behind the scenes

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:24.959
to change Cordo documents to their final format. And so, it's very rich and it lets you control

00:05:24.959 --> 00:05:29.760
your document very, very specifically, while still being easy to read and write.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:36.079
And so, in summary, with Cordo, you take text, you take code, and you produce something

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:41.679
that you want to share with others, things like documents, and web pages, and blog posts, and books.

00:05:42.399 --> 00:05:46.000
And as mentioned, you can do it with a variety of programming languages.

00:05:48.239 --> 00:05:53.519
You can do it in your favorite editor. So, today, we'll be primarily working in RStudio,

00:05:53.519 --> 00:05:57.440
but if you're a Positron user, VS Code user, you could also use those.

00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:06.079
Again, you can publish to a variety of outputs, depending on your needs, or you could do it

00:06:06.799 --> 00:06:12.160
multiple outputs at once. Say you want HTML and PDF, you could do that from a single source.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:18.559
And finally, in terms of publishing it, you can put it on a variety of platforms,

00:06:18.559 --> 00:06:22.239
such as PositConnect, or Confluence, or GitHub Pages, and so on.

